<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-03-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-03-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="489" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d489">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/2858</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Ramer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-03-25"><hi rend="italic">March 25,
                                1922</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received April 14.]</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 38</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>:</p>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                        <p>Colonel Tracy arrived in Managua March 17th after spending over a month
                            of investigation of conditions on the Nicaraguan-Honduranean frontier.
                            He reported that the revolutionary movement in Honduras is very popular
                            on the Honduranean border and may assume serious proportions at any
                            time; also that the Nicaraguan Government officials in the border
                            districts are giving moral support to this movement by their inactivity
                            …</p>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John E. Ramer</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>